    ```javascript
function minOperations(nums) {
    const n = nums.length;
    let i = 0, j = n - 1;
    let operations = 0;

    while (i < j) {
        if (nums[i] === nums[j]) {
            i++;
            j--;
        } else if (nums[i] < nums[j]) {
            nums[i + 1] += nums[i];
            i++;
            operations++;
        } else {
            nums[j - 1] += nums[j];
            j--;
            operations++;
        }
    }
    return operations;
}
```

    The algorithm uses two pointers, `i` and `j`, initializing them to the start and end of the array, respectively. It then enters a loop, moving these pointers inwards and comparing the values in the array at these indices. If the values are equal, the pointers are moved inwards without performing any operation. If the values are not equal, an operation is performed to make the smaller value equal to the larger one. The loop continues until the pointers cross each other. The number of operations performed is returned as the result.

The algorithm has a complexity of O(n) as it iterates through the input array once.

